===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|Rine}}, {{m|enm|Ryne}}, from {{inh|en|ang|Rīn|t=the Rhine}}, from {{der|en|gmh|-}}, ultimately {{der|en|gem-pro|*Rīnaz}}, from {{der|en|cel-gau|Rēnos}}, from a {{w|Pre-Celtic}} or {{der|en|cel-pro|*Reinos}}; one of a class of river names built from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₃reyH-||to move, flow, run}}.<ref>{{R:ine:IEW|326}} etymon [http://www.utexas.edu/cola/centers/lrc/ielex/R/P0498.html 3. er- : or- : r-] 'to move, set in motion' (laryngealistic reconstruction as "*h₁reiH").</ref> Cognate with {{cog|goh|Rīn}} {{gloss|"the Rhine"; > {{cog|de|Rhein}}}}, {{cog|non|Rín|t=the Rhine}}, {{cog|nl|Rijn|t=the Rhine}}.

Related also to Latin {{m|la|rivus}} "river"), in Celtic with an ''-n-'' suffix as in {{cog|sga|rian|rīan|sea}} (more at {{m|en|run}}).

The spelling with ''Rh-'' is due to the influence of Ancient Greek {{m|grc|Ῥῆνος}} (via {{etyl|fr|en}} {{m|fr|Rhin}}).

